      <p>To implement Gibbs sampling, we initialize the allelic compositions to random values and then draw a value for the allelic composition of each sample from its corresponding conditional distribution. Each newly drawn allelic composition value is used to update the conditional distributions of the rest of the samples and this procedure is repeated for a large number of iterations to allow the Markov chain to converge. Upon convergence, samples drawn from the conditionals may be assumed to come from the required joint distribution. We then infer as a point estimate of each allelic composition <italic>S</italic>, the most frequently drawn state.</p>
